          <msContents>
            <summary>Manuscript used for contemplation and study and is a short Hindu philosophical treatise and commentary on the Great saying (mahāvākya), particularly the phrase, You are that (tat tvam asi), often functioning as a mantra and derived from late Vedic upaniṣads. The work is written from the perspective of the Advaita (non-dualism) Vedanta school of philosophy.</summary>
            <textLang>In Sanskrit</textLang>
            <msItem>
              <title>Vākyavṛtti</title>
              <author>Śaṅkarācārya</author>
              <colophon>Colophon: iti śrīmatparamahaṃsaparivrājakācāryaviracitaṃ vākyavṛttiḥ samāptā // (f. 2v).</colophon>
            </msItem>
